// NOTE: Integrated into the Fusion FSN tree for migration traceability.
// CONTENT:
// TensorWeave, a high-performance, fault-tolerant, and secure runtime written in Rust.
// 
// This system maps your requested verbs to specific architectural components:
// Correct: Input Validation & Schema Enforcement (Serde/Validator).
// Assist: Telemetry & Heuristics (Tracing/Metrics).
// Optimize: Tensor Decomposition & Graph Rewriting (ndarray/Graph Traversal).
// Secure: Cryptographic signing of models & Memory Safety (Ring/Rust Ownership).
// Stabilize: Numerical stability checks (NaN/Inf detection).
// Adjust: Dynamic configuration (Hot-reloading).
// Accelerate: Async execution & SIMD (Tokio/Rayon).
// Maintain: Self-healing loops & Health Checks.
// 
// 1. Product Info Sheet: TensorWeave
// Product Name: TensorWeave Core Version: 1.0.0-alpha Description: TensorWeave is an "interwoven flow" engine built in Rust designed to orchestrate high-dimensional data operations. Unlike standard math libraries, TensorWeave acts as a managed runtime. It wraps raw tensor operations in a protective, optimizing shell that automatically handles security verification, numerical stability, and hardware acceleration selection.
// 
// Key Capabilities:
// Self-Healing Pipelines: Automatically detects numerical instability (exploding gradients/NaNs) and attempts recovery or decomposition.
// Secure Compute: Enforces cryptographic signatures on tensor data to prevent model poisoning.
// Auto-Optimization: Analyzes tensor shapes at runtime to suggest or apply decompositions (CP/Tensor Train) for memory efficiency.
// Async-First: Built on tokio to handle concurrent data ingestion and processing without blocking the computation graph.
// 
// 2. Architecture & Developer Guide
// System Architecture
// The system uses a Middleware/Interceptor Pattern. A TensorFlow (the struct, not Google's library) is a collection of Processors. Data flows through these processors.
// 
// 
// graph LR
//     A[Input Data] --> B(Ingestion Layer)
//     B --> C{Flow Engine}
//     C --> D[Secure: Auth/Sign Check]
//     D --> E[Correct: Shape/Type Val]
//     E --> F[Optimize: Auto-Decomposition]
//     F --> G[Stabilize: Numerical Check]
//     G --> H[Accelerate: Compute Execution]
//     H --> I[Maintain: Metrics/Logging]
//     I --> J[Output Tensor]
// Directory Structure
// 
// 
// tensor_weave/
// ├── Cargo.toml
// ├── Dockerfile
// ├── .github/workflows/ci.yml
// ├── src/
// │   ├── main.rs          # Entry point
// │   ├── lib.rs           # Lib root
// │   ├── core.rs          # Tensor abstractions
// │   ├── flow.rs          # The Interwoven Engine
// │   ├── processors/      # The Verbs
// │   │   ├── mod.rs
// │   │   ├── secure.rs
// │   │   ├── optimize.rs
// │   │   ├── stabilize.rs
// │   │   └── maintain.rs
// │   └── util.rs
// └── tests/
//     └── integration_test.rs
// 
// 3. Technical Sheet & System RequirementsStatus: DocumentationAction: Specification DefinitionProgress: 60%CategoryRequirementDescriptionOSLinux / macOS / WindowsSupports x86_64 and aarch64.LanguageRust 1.70+Requires specific async trait features.Memory8GB+ RAMRecommended for large tensor decomposition testing.HardwareAVX2 SupportFor ndarray vectorization improvements.DependenciesOpenSSL / RingRequired for the Security layer.
// 
// 4. User Guide: How to Use TensorWeave
// Define your Data: Create TensorData objects representing your high-dimensional inputs.
// Configure the Engine: Instantiate TensorWeaveEngine.
// Select Interceptors: Add the processors you need. If you are doing trusted local work, you might skip SecureProcessor. If you are working with unstable experimental data, ensure StabilizeProcessor is early in the chain.
// Run: Await engine.run_flow(data).
// Observe: Check standard output or configured logs for telemetry regarding optimization decisions and stability corrections.
// 
// 5. Product Guide: Design & Roadmap
// Current State (v1.0):
// Basic Interwoven Flow Architecture.
// Plug-and-play middleware system.
// Rudimentary self-healing (NaN removal).
// 
// 6. Roadmap (v2.0 - Future):
// Distributed Tensors: Implement MPI or Ray bindings to split tensors across network nodes.
// Quantum Simulation: Add a QuantumStateProcessor that uses tensor networks (MPS/PEPS) to simulate quantum bits.
// JIT Compilation: Integrate TVM or MLIR into the AccelerateProcessor to compile tensor graphs to machine code at runtime.
// 
// Status: Quality Check Action: Review Output Subtask: Verification against user constraints Progress: 99%
